<hr>
<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br><br>
When you use another person&#8217;s ideas in your writing, list the author&#8217;s name, in parentheses, immediately following the cited material. If the entry begins with the title, provide the title of the brochure in italics. Abbreviate the title if it is longer than a noun phrase. For example, <em>Faulkner&#8217;s Southern Novels</em> consists entirely of a noun phrase (a noun <em>Novels</em> preceded by two modifiers) and wouldn&#8217;t be shortened. By contrast <em>Faulkner&#8217;s Novels of the South</em> would be shortened to its noun phrase <em>Faulkner’s Novels</em>. The abbreviated title should begin with the word by which it is alphabetised in the Works Cited. If the title does not begin with a noun phrase, cite the first word if it is enough to direct the reader to the correct entry. For further information on abbreviating titles, see 3.2.1 in the <a href="http://west-sydney-primo.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/UWS-ALMA:default_scope:UWS-ALMA21186157620001571" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">MLA Handbook (8th edition)</a>.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Buses run on schedule&hellip; (<em>Transport</em>). 
</blockquote>
<br>
<br>
Or include the author’s name in your sentence. If you are using the title instead, provide the full title in the sentence.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	The Western Sydney University <em>Transport Access Guide: Penrith Campus</em> shows that&hellip;
</blockquote>
